    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-08-10T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-08-10T00:00:00-05:00" n="310"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d310">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">741.53/157</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">President</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-08-10">August 10,
                            1943</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="center">
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Memorandum for the President</hi>
                </p>
                <p>There is submitted herewith a draft of a telegram<note n="1" xml:id="d310fn1">The
                        draft was approved without change. For the text of the telegram, as sent on
                        August 12, 1943, see <hi rend="italic">infra.</hi>
                    </note> which it is proposed to send to London in connection with the secret
                    negotiations now in progress between the British Government and the Prime
                    Minister of Portugal. The conditions set forth in London’s telegram no. 4285 of
                    June 29, 1943,<note n="2" xml:id="d310fn2">See <ref target="frus1943v02#pg_534">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1943, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">ii</hi>, pp. 534</ref>–<ref
                            target="frus1943v02#pg_535">535</ref>.</note> are as follows: <list>
                        <label>(1)</label>
                        <item>That at the close of hostilities British troops would be withdrawn
                            from <gloss target="#t_Bracken1">
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Bracken</hi>
                            </gloss>, and</item>
                        <label>(2)</label>
                        <item>That Portuguese sovereignty will be maintained over all Portuguese
                            colonies.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>There is attached a copy of a communication addressed to the Department by the
                    Joint Chiefs of Staff on August 9, 1943,<note n="3" xml:id="d310fn3">The
                        communication referred to has not been identified, but it was perhaps either
                        a copy of the paper of August 4, 1943, <hi rend="italic">post</hi>, <ref
                            target="#pg_616">p. 616</ref>, or an early draft of the Joint Chiefs of
                        Staff paper referred to in Hull’s telegram to Winant, <hi rend="italic"
                            >infra.</hi>
                    </note> upon which the second paragraph of the draft telegram is based.<note
                        n="4" xml:id="d310fn4">Hull’s memorandum was returned to the Department of
                        State on August 11, 1943, bearing Roosevelt’s handwritten endorsement “OK
                        FDR”.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>C[<hi rend="smallcaps">ordell</hi>] H[<hi rend="smallcaps"
                        >ull</hi>]</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
